@NODE "AGW.info"

 The 'AGW' icon.
 ---------------

 An ordinary text file is magically transformed into an AGuide file. At
 first I only had that text sheet, the AGuide window and the small arrow.
 Later I added the cross over the text file and the magic sparkles. So it
 became a real @{"MagicWB" LINK "What is MagicWB 2.0?"} icon.
 For more information refer to this chapter: @{"The 'AGW' drawer." LINK "AGW.dr.info"}.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Brain Cloud.info"

 The 'Brain Cloud' icon.
 -----------------------

 A reproduction of an icon supplied together with 'QuarterbackTools'.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "CatEdit.info"

 The 'CatEdit' icon.
 -------------------

 The explanation of this icon has actually allready been given. If you'd
 like to read it again then click this button @{" · " LINK "CatEdit.dr.info"}.
 That explanation is just the same except that this icon is bigger and
 that we first see three books and after clicking we see four.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "DISCovery.info"

 The 'DISCovery' icon.
 ---------------------

 With this program I used to fix 'broken' disks manually. (Just to show
 off, I do know completely how to work with this program.) It is the same
 as 'DiskSalv' but this one doesn't work automatically. It shows a disk
 in blocks, headers etc. which you can edit with the keyboard.
 I have taken the 'ShowConfig' icon in the SYS:Tools drawer, erased the
 chips and replaced them with some binary numbers. The 'DISCovery' was
 born!

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Disk Eraser.info"

 The 'Disk Eraser' icon.
 -----------------------

 Another reproduction of an icon supplied together with 'QuarterbackTools'.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "DiskSalv.info"

 The 'DiskSalv' icon.
 -----------------------

 A disk, sadly, helplessly in the water... But after a brief click it ends
 up on a beach, still wet but much happier. Our disk is salvaged!

 P.S.: Also see: @{"The 'DiskSalv' drawer." LINK "DiskSalv.dr.info"}.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "DOSTrace.info"

 The 'DOSTrace' icon.
 --------------------

 'DOSTrace' traces every icon, file byte etc. which is opened by a
 program. It's very handy for debugging purposes or to find out why a
 program doesn't work with your configuration.
 The icon is exactly the same as the window opened by the program, only
 smaller.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Encryptor.info"

 The 'Encryptor' icon.
 ---------------------

 Well... We see a hard disk on this icon, but when we click it, it becomes
 encrypted. So we still see something that looks like a hard disk, yet we
 can't tell for sure what it is.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "File Eraser.info"

 The 'File Eraser' icon.
 -----------------------

 Yeah... Sure... Guessed right... A reproduction of an icon supplied
 together with 'QuarterbackTools'.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "FinalWriter.info"

 The 'FinalWriter' icon.
 -----------------------

 Another reproduction. The icon is the same as the original, I just
 repainted it as a @{"MagicWB" LINK "What is MagicWB 2.0?"} icon. Worked out pretty well, don't you think?
 Also refer to the following chapter: @{"The 'FinalWriter' drawer." LINK "FinalWriter.dr.info"}.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "FinalData.info"

 The 'FinalData' icon.
 ---------------------

 This is a quicky, thus not that good. It shows a database and when
 clicked one specific file comes up; that's all.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "FixDisk.info"

 The 'FixDisk' icon.
 -------------------

 Fixdisk is one of the first programs which were able to fix disks
 themselves. So no manually editing anymore!
 For the creation of the icon I took a disk which suffered from severe
 meltdown. (I left it too long on the cental heating to dry, after it fell
 in a pond 8).) Since 'FixDisk' is supposed to fix disks, it should be
 able to fix this one too, I thought. And indeed, with a little magic and
 a click of the left mousebutton, the disk is restored back to its original
 state.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "FreeSpace.info"

 The 'FreeSpace' icon.
 ---------------------

 'FreeSpace' is a tiny program which shows the percentage free on all
 mounted volumes, and pours this into a nice bar graph.
 The icon gives a pretty good idea of what the program looks like and what
 it does. Simply because it's exactly the same as the program itself, only
 smaller.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "GelDecruncher.info"

 The 'GelDecruncher' icon.
 -------------------------

 I must say I don't like this icon too much. This is supposed to be a
 wobbly gel mass, which expands when clicked. A very simple explanation of
 a decrunch routine.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "GigaMem-Startup.info"

 The 'GigaMem-Startup' icon.
 ---------------------------

 The idea is that the giant hard disk-chip gets installed in your system
 at bootup. Your computer is then, normally, provided with electricity and
 so will that chip be when clicked and when installed 8).

 "We have a connection captain!"  - Geordy LaForge

 Additional information: @{"The 'GigaMem' drawer." LINK "GigaMem.dr.info"}, @{"The 'GigaMem' icon." LINK "GigaMem.info"} and
 @{"The 'GigaMemPrefs' icon." LINK "GigaMemPrefs.info"}.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "GigaMem.info"

 The 'GigaMem' icon.
 -------------------

 As said before 'GigaMem' combines your memory with your hard disk. Just
 to be sure we'll make the addition to see how I came to that magic chip:
 one small chip and a small hard disk equals a big chip combined with
 still the same small hard disk. Stunned, huh?
 More information is found in the following chapters:
 @{"The 'GigaMem' drawer." LINK "GigaMem.dr.info"}, @{"The 'GigaMem-Startup' icon." LINK "GigaMem-Startup.info"} and
 @{"The 'GigaMemPrefs' icon." LINK "GigaMemPrefs.info"}.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "GuiArc.info"

 The 'GuiArc' icon.
 ------------------

 This is one more reproduction of the old icon. I again repainted it into
 a real @{"MagicWB" LINK "What is MagicWB 2.0?"} icon and... You've just got to admit it... It does look
 nice.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "HandyDMS.info"

 The 'HandyDMS' icon.
 --------------------

 A reproduction... Is that sufficient? If not click here: @{" · " LINK "HandyDMS.dr.info"}.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Imploder.info"

 The 'Imploder' icon.
 --------------------

 Hmmm... Indeed... It looks very much like the old one, except that it has
 a magic undertone, don't you think? I'll be honest, it's a reproduction.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Keystroke Finder.info"

 The 'Keystroke Finder' icon.
 ----------------------------

 Again a reproduction of an icon supplied together with 'QuarterbackTools'.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Locator.info"

 The 'Locator' icon.
 -------------------

 Hmmm... Indeed... A a reproduction of an icon supplied together with...
 Guess with what... 'QuarterbackTools' naturally.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Mod2Smp.info"

 The 'Mod2Smp' icon.
 -------------------

 'Mod2Smp' swallows a 'ProTracker' module, chews it and spits one of the,
 by user selected, patterns out as a sample. It's very useful to make
 beats. I guess the icon will explain itself now.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "NewMode.info"

 The 'NewMode' icon.
 -------------------

 This is a reproduction, not as clear as the original icon though. We see
 a monitor with a small screen on it. When clicked this screen is promoted
 to fill the entire monitor. That's exactly what 'NewMode' does, the
 promoting of EVERY screen that is opened to a user definable resolution.
 You can refer to this chapter for additional information:
 @{"The 'NewMode' drawer." LINK "NewMode.dr.info"}.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "QB FKeys.info"

 The 'QB FKeys' icon.
 --------------------

 (Sigh) ... ... ... A reproduction... Again... There'll come some more, I
 can tell ya!

@ENDNODE



@NODE "QB Macros.info"

 The 'QB Macros' icon.
 ---------------------

 See, what'd I tell ya? Hmmm? Yep, this is one of them... Reproduction...
 'QuarterbackTools'...

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Quarterback.info"

 The 'Quarterback' icon.
 -----------------------

 This is a reproduction of the original icon. I guess you know by now what
 that means. Well, I must say, I never paid much attention to this icon
 but now I've got it figured out. I never knew what that football was
 doing there, now I know. Quarterback is a term from the American-football
 sport. Hey, creating @{"MagicWB" LINK "What is MagicWB 2.0?"} icons isn't so bad, you know!

@ENDNODE



@NODE "QuarterbackTools.info"

 The 'QuarterbackTools' icon.
 ----------------------------

 I guess it'll never stop... Another stupid reproduction.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "QuickGrab.info"

 The 'QuickGrab' icon.
 ---------------------

 A screen is grabbed and when clicked saved to the disk. Nice, hey?
 Additional info: @{"The 'QuickGrab' drawer." LINK "QuickGrab.dr.info"}

@ENDNODE


@NODE "ReOrg.info"

 The 'ReOrg' icon.
 -----------------

 It's the same explanation as @{"the 'ReOrg' drawer icon" LINK "ReOrg.dr.info"}, except that the
 magic from @{"MagicWB" LINK "What is MagicWB 2.0?"} is used here to reorganize the disk to a shiny new
 one.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Replicator.info"

 The 'Replicator' icon.
 ----------------------

 And them reproductions keep on coming.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Schedule Pro.info"

 The 'Schedule Pro' icon.
 ------------------------

 I'll never stop reproducing if the icons are good enough.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "SnoopDos.info"

 The 'SnoopDos' icon.
 --------------------

 'SnoopDos' snoops almost everything that is opened by the disk operating
 system. The icon is the same as the window opened by 'SnoopDos'.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "System Mover.info"

 The 'System Mover' icon.
 ------------------------

 Aha! Finally... This is NO reproduction. I made this one up myself. We
 see a small hard disk and a big hard disk. Normally your SYS: partition
 is the smallest, so the small hard disk represents the 'System'. When we
 give this icon a click, an arrow pops up meaning that the system will be
 moved to another (bigger) hard disk. Nice huh...

@ENDNODE



@NODE "TranslateCatEdit.info"

 The 'TranslateCatEdit' icon.
 ----------------------------

 A fine reproduction of the old dull icon.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "VBS.info"

 The 'VBS' icon.
 ---------------

 A traditional icon. A hard disk with a video tape. When clicked another
 video tape appears, representing another finished backup.
 Refer to chapter @{"The 'VBS' drawer." LINK "VBS.dr.info"} for more information.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "XCopy.info"

 The 'XCopy' icon.
 -----------------

 Amother incredibly cool reproduction; looks much nicer than the original
 one, if I do say so myself.

@ENDNODE



